Title:
Behavioral blocking and containment (Microsoft Defender for Endpoint)

Type:
Documentation

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This Microsoft Defender for Endpoint document explains “behavioral blocking and containment,” a set of protections that stop threats based on observed behaviors and process trees, including after execution has begun. It addresses modern fileless/LOLBins, polymorphic malware, and human-operated attacks that evade signature-based defenses by using AI/ML and cross-signal correlation. The write-up outlines how multiple Defender components work together: Attack Surface Reduction (ASR) rules (policy-driven prevention), client behavioral blocking (ML-based on-endpoint blocking/remediation), feedback-loop/rapid protection (org-wide blocking propagation), and EDR in block mode (post-breach blocking even when Defender AV isn’t primary). It provides examples of blocked techniques such as LSASS credential dumping, injection/hollowing, UAC bypass, AV tampering, C2 activity, boot record modification, pass-the-hash, and root certificate installation. It’s most useful for Blue Teams/SOC and security engineers designing endpoint prevention + EDR response, and for Red Teams to understand which behaviors commonly trigger automatic containment.

Technical Focus:
- Behavior-based detection using process trees and ML classifiers (cloud + client)
- Attack Surface Reduction (ASR) rules and policy enforcement
- Client behavioral blocking and automatic remediation
- Feedback-loop (rapid protection) org-wide blocking propagation
- EDR in block mode (post-breach blocking independent of primary AV)
- Incident/alert correlation in Microsoft Defender XDR

Use Cases:
- Configure and validate ASR rules to prevent common attacker behaviors
- Enable and operationalize EDR in block mode for post-compromise blocking
- Tune SOC workflows around alerts/incidents generated by behavior-based detections
- Assess endpoint resilience against common tradecraft (injection, LSASS access, UAC bypass, C2)
- Red-team test planning to anticipate Defender behavioral containment triggers

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, Microsoft Defender XDR, behavioral blocking, containment, machine learning, device learning, process tree, Attack Surface Reduction, ASR rules, EDR in block mode, feedback-loop blocking, rapid protection, LSASS credential dumping, cross-process injection, process hollowing, UAC bypass, AV tampering, command and control, pass-the-hash, NTLM relay, Juicy Potato, boot record modification, fileless malware, living off the land (LOLBins)